contents.rsbHtml:
Dither.dx

"A common use of dither is converting a grayscale image to black and white, such that the density of black dots in the new image approximates the average gray level in the original." [From https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dither]
contents.rsbText:
' # Dither.dx
  "A common use of dither is converting a grayscale image to black and white, 
   such that the density of black dots in the new image approximates 
   the average gray level in the original." 
  [From [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dither](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dither)]

contents.rsbHtml: Here we represent grayscale images as matrices of floats with continuous values between 0 (white) and 1 (black). The quantized results after dithering will be matrices of booleans arising from a pixel-wise thresholding. Each dithering algorithm below uses its own rule of choosing a threshold value, resulting in distinct styles.

def rand(k:Key) -> Float =
  exponent_bits : Word32 = 1065353216 # 1065353216 = 127 << 23
  mantissa_bits = (high_word k .&. 8388607)  # 8388607 == (1 << 23) - 1
  bits = exponent_bits .|. mantissa_bits
  %bitcast(Float, bits) - 1.0

contents.rsbHtml:
Round 3: Ordered dithering

Ordered dithering uses a small threshold matrix that is periodically tiled over the target image. We achieve this by wrapping the pixel indices i and j into the range of the small matrix mat to retrieve the threshold.
contents.rsbText:
' # Round 3: Ordered dithering
  Ordered dithering uses a small threshold matrix that is periodically tiled over the target
  image. We achieve this by wrapping the pixel indices i and j into the range of
  the small matrix `mat` to retrieve the threshold.

contents.rsbHtml: def dither_ordered(mat: mh=>mw=>Float, img: h=>w=>Float) -> (h=>w=>Bool) given (mh|Ix, mw|Ix, h|Ix, w|Ix) = for i j. img[i, j] > mat[wrap_periodic mh (ordinal i), wrap_periodic mw (ordinal j)]
contents.rsbText:
def dither_ordered(mat: mh=>mw=>Float, img: h=>w=>Float) -> (h=>w=>Bool) given (mh|Ix, mw|Ix, h|Ix, w|Ix) =
  for i j. img[i, j] > mat[wrap_periodic mh (ordinal i), wrap_periodic mw (ordinal j)]
